{"id":"2111.07636","submitter":"Qi-Feng Wu","authors":"Qi-Feng Wu","title":"Entanglement Classification via Operator Size","comments":"16 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph hep-th","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  In this work, a systematic approach to classifying multipartite entanglement\nis developed. I show that the operator size is closely related to the\nentanglement structure. Given a generic quantum state, I define a series of\nsubspaces by operators of different sizes acting on it. The information about\nthe entanglement is encoded into these subspaces. With the dimension of these\nsubspaces as coefficients, I define a polynomial which I call the entanglement\npolynomial. The entanglement polynomial induces a monoid homomorphism from\nquantum states to polynomials. By taking the quotient over the kernel of the\nhomomorphism, we obtain an isomorphism from entanglement classes to\npolynomials. It implies that we can characterize and find the building blocks\nof entanglement by polynomial factorization. Two states share the same\nentanglement polynomial if they are equivalent under the stochastic local\noperations and classical communication. To calculate the entanglement\npolynomial practically, I construct a series of states, called renormalized\nstates, whose ranks are related to the coefficients of the entanglement\npolynomial.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 15 Nov 2021 09:52:12 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 18 Mar 2022 07:05:35 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 21 Mar 2022 09:52:54 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 29 Mar 2022 15:09:51 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Thu, 21 Apr 2022 09:59:00 GMT"},{"version":"v6","created":"Sun, 3 Jul 2022 15:00:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-07-05"}
