{"id":"2111.07818","submitter":"In\\^es Louren\\c{c}o","authors":"In\\^es Louren\\c{c}o, Rebecka Winqvist, Cristian R. Rojas, Bo Wahlberg","title":"A Teacher-Student Markov Decision Process-based Framework for Online\n  Correctional Learning","comments":"8 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.LG cs.SY eess.SY","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A classical learning setting typically concerns an agent/student who collects\ndata, or observations, from a system in order to estimate a certain property of\ninterest. Correctional learning is a type of cooperative teacher-student\nframework where a teacher, who has partial knowledge about the system, has the\nability to observe and alter (correct) the observations received by the student\nin order to improve the accuracy of its estimate. In this paper, we show how\nthe variance of the estimate of the student can be reduced with the help of the\nteacher. We formulate the corresponding online problem - where the teacher has\nto decide, at each time instant, whether or not to change the observations due\nto a limited budget - as a Markov decision process, from which the optimal\npolicy is derived using dynamic programming. We validate the framework in\nnumerical experiments, and compare the optimal online policy with the one from\nthe batch setting.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 15 Nov 2021 15:01:00 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 29 Mar 2022 12:35:44 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-03-30"}
